TOP50_BATCH9: dict[str, str] = {
    "Kiddush b'Makom Seudah means sanctifying Shabbat or Yom Tov, typically with blessings over wine, in the same place you eat a meal afterwards. You would not fulfill Kiddush if you recited it and left without eating there. On Shabbat night, the meal should include bread (hamotzi) per most poskim. On Yom Tov or daytime Kiddush, other foods may qualify in some cases; ask your rav. If you make Kiddush in one room, the meal should follow there and not in a different space.": "Киддуш бмаком сеуда означает, что киддуш произносят там, где будет трапеза — иначе обязанность не выполнена. В пятницу вечером трапеза должна включать хлеб (ха-моци) по мнению большинства посеким. В Йом Тов или дневной киддуш в некоторых случаях подходят другие продукты — спросите рава. Если киддуш в одной комнате, едите там же, а не в другом месте.",
    "Kiddush b'Makom Seudah — Kiddush b'Makom Seudah means sanctifying Shabbat or Yom Tov, typically with blessings over wine, in the same place you eat a meal afterwards. You would not fulfill Kiddush if you recited it and left without eating there. On Shabbat night, the meal should include bread (hamotzi) per most poskim. On Yom Tov or daytime Kiddush, other foods may qualify in some cases; ask your rav. If you make Kiddush in one room, the meal should follow there and not in a different space.": "киддуш бмаком сеуда — киддуш там, где едите; иначе обязанность не выполнена.",
    "Kinot — elegies read on Tisha B'Av mourning the Temple": "кинот — элегии в Тиша бе-Ав, оплакивающие Храм и беды народа.",
    "Kol Chamira": "Коль хамира",
    "Korech": "корех",
    "Koteiv": "котейв",
    "Learn about Kotzer — reaping and detaching growth from its source! ✂️ This is one of the most everyday melachot: picking fruit from a tree, plucking a flower, or detaching anything from its source of growth. It traces back to the Mishkan, where wheat and dye-herbs were harvested. The rule is absolute: if it grows, you cannot sever it. This even includes picking herbs from a potted plant on your kitchen windowsill. To protect this law, the Sages even forbade making direct use of a tree on Shabbat—so climbing trees, leaning on them, or hanging hammocks is out. Ever wonder why people don't pick flowers or climb trees on Shabbat? This is why. Shabbat teaches us to enjoy creation without constantly taking from it or disrupting it. Learn more!": "Узнайте о Коцер — жатве и отделении роста от источника! ✂️ В Мишкане срезали травы для красителей. Коцер — срывать, резать или отделять растение от корня или земли. В Шаббат запрещено срывать цветы, листья для украшения или плоды с дерева. Нельзя лазить по деревьям и использовать их как опору. Узнайте больше!",
    "Learn about Losh — kneading and forming a mass from separate ingredients! 🍞 Think dough: flour + water + mixing = one unified blob. In the Mishkan, Losh was a key agricultural step used when mixing water with the ground herb powders to make dyes, as well as kneading the flour to bake the Showbread. On Shabbat, this melacha prohibits combining a finely divided powder or small solid particles with a liquid to form a single, cohesive paste or thick mass. This restriction directly affects how people prepare everyday items like baby cereal, instant oatmeal, mustard, or even certain dense textures of egg salad. To avoid a Torah-level violation, the halacha requires using specific workarounds when a paste must be made, such as changing the normal order of ingredients (for instance, pouring the liquid into the bowl before adding the powder) and mixing the ingredients with an unusual motion (Shinui), like employing a crisscross slicing movement with a knife instead of a standard circular stir. This is why Shabbat challah is baked before the day of rest begins, since the creative act of unifying separate elements into a brand new entity belongs entirely to Friday, leaving us to enjoy the completed creation on Shabbat. Learn more!": "Узнайте о Лош — замешивании и образовании массы! 🍞 В Мишкане замешивали тесто и красители. Лош запрещает соединять порошок с жидкостью в единую густую массу в Шаббат — тесто, кашу, горчицу. Обходные пути: другой порядок ингредиентов и необычное движение (шинуи). Хала пекут в пятницу. Узнайте больше!",
    "Learn about one of the most surprising 'superpowers' in a kosher kitchen: the Case of the Spicy Onion! In the world of kosher law, flavor usually needs high heat to travel from a pot or a knife into your food. If everything is cold, tastes don't transfer and a simple rinse-off solves any mix-up (as long as it doesn't sit for 24 hours). But there is a fascinating exception called Davar Charif — literally 'a sharp thing' — where the rules of physics seem to change. Think of foods like onions, lemons, or hot peppers as having a sort of chemical heat. These foods are so 'aggressive' that they don't need a stove to move flavor around. If you take a cold knife that is only used for meat and slice into a sharp, raw onion, that onion actually 'squeezes' the meat essence out of the steel blade. Even though no one turned on a flame, that onion is now considered a meat product. If you accidentally tossed it into a bowl of cream cheese, you'd have a real kosher conundrum on your hands! What makes Davar Charif even more 'powerful' is how it handles time. Usually, if a pot or knife hasn't been used for 24 hours, any flavor trapped inside its pores is considered 'stale' and loses its status. But a sharp food can actually 'reawaken' that sleeping flavor. A sharp onion can pull flavor out of a knife that hasn't touched a steak in years, making the onion 'meat' all over again. This is why many people keep a special 'Pareve' knife — one that is neither meat nor dairy — specifically for their davar charif fruits and veggies. Learn more!": "Узнайте о «суперсиле» кошерной кухни — давар хариф! 🧅 Острые продукты (лук, лимон, перец) «выжимают» вкус мяса из ножа даже без огня. Поэтому многие держат отдельный парвe-нож для овощей. Парвe — нейтральное: не мясо и не молочное. Узнайте больше!",
    "Learn about the Nazirite vow — a unique spiritual journey! 🍇✂️💀 A Nazir (Nazirite) voluntarily undertakes three powerful abstentions for a minimum of 30 days: (1) No Grape Products: Absolutely nothing from the vine – no grapes, wine, grape juice, or even grape seeds/skins. This 'fence around the fence' prevents even a hint of indulgence. (2) No Haircuts: The Nazir allows their hair to grow wild, a visible sign of their dedication. At the vow's end, the hair is shaved and brought as an offering. (3) No Contact with the Dead: Even close family members (like a parent or child) cannot be touched, emphasizing a profound level of purity. The ultimate challenge: if the Nazir becomes ritually impure from a corpse, the clock resets! They must shave, bring sacrifices, and start the entire count over. The Torah calls a Nazir 'kadosh' (holy), sparking a fascinating debate among the Sages: Is this extra holiness praiseworthy? The Talmud embraces both perspectives. While no longer widely practiced (because there would be no way to offer the sacrifices required at the end of the nazirite vow period, since there's no Temple) the nazir teaches us about profound self-discipline and the pursuit of holiness. Source: Numbers 6; Rambam, Hilchot Nezirut 1; Talmud, Nazir.": "Узнайте об обете назира! 🍇✂️ Три воздержания минимум на 30 дней: (1) ничего от лозы, (2) без стрижки, (3) без соприкосновения с мёртвыми. Осквернение от трупа — отсчёт сначала. Тора называет назира «кадош». Сегодня почти не практикуется без Храма. Источник: Бемидбар 6; Рамбам, Илхот Незирут 1.",
    "Learn about the Temple Mount's dimensions! 🏛️ Mount Moriah, the Temple Mount where the Holy Temple stood, measured 500 cubits by 500 cubits and was surrounded by a wall. Did you know? The entire earth beneath was hollowed out and supported by arches to prevent ritual impurity from graves below!": "Узнайте о размерах Храмовой горы! 🏛️ Мориа — 500×500 локтей со стеной. Землю под ней выдолбили и поддержали арками, чтобы не было тумат меот от могил внизу. Узнайте больше!",
    "Learn the Rambam's surprisingly specific health guidelines! 🍽️ Written over 900 years ago, many of the Rambam's (Maimonides) health guidelines in Hilchot De'ot 4 are remarkably validated by modern medicine. He teaches: 'Maintaining a healthy body is part of serving Hashem, because it is impossible to understand or know Hashem if one is ill.' Here's his practical wisdom: Don't eat until you're stuffed! Stop eating when about 75% full. Eat slowly and in a seated position. Avoid drinking liquids excessively during meals. Don't sleep immediately after eating; wait a few hours. Prioritize sleep during the night; daytime napping is generally discouraged. Exercise is essential – the Rambam asserts that lack of physical movement is a primary cause of illness. Avoid foods that are clearly harmful.": "Изучите конкретные советы Рамбама о здоровье! 🍽️ В «Хилхот Деот» 4: здоровое тело — часть служения В-гу. Не ешьте до отвала — останавливайтесь на ~75%. Ешьте медленно, сидя. Не засыпайте сразу после еды. Ночной сон важнее дневного. Движение необходимо. Избегайте явно вредной пищи.",
    "Level up your character: Study Pirkei Avot! 📚 Pirkei Avot, the 'Ethics of the Fathers,' is a treasure trove of timeless wisdom for daily life and middot (character development). Each short teaching offers profound, practical guidance on how to be a truly good person, treat others with kindness and integrity, and serve Hashem with humility and intention. These aren't just ancient sayings; they are foundational Jewish values that have shaped our ethical framework for over 2,000 years! Make it a weekly habit: pick your favorite lesson from any chapter and reflect on how you can apply its wisdom to your own life today. It's a spiritual workout for your soul! Source: Mishnah, Pirkei Avot; Talmud, Bava Kama 30a (regarding the importance of ethical conduct).": "Развивайте характер: изучайте Пиркей Авот! 📚 «Этика отцов» — практическая мудрость о характере, доброте и служении В-гу. Еженедельная привычка — духовная тренировка души. Источник: Мишна, Пиркей Авот; Талмуд, Бава Кама 30а.",
    "Maaser kesafim is setting aside about ten percent of net income for tzedakah after expenses. It trains that income is entrusted, not owned absolutely. Priorities: local poor, Torah learning, Israel. If you cannot give ten percent without hardship, give what you can and ask your rav.": "маасер кесафим — откладывать ~10% чистого дохода на тредаку. Приоритеты: местные бедные, Тора, Израиль. При трудностях — сколько можете; спросите рава.",
    "Master the art of loving rebuke! 💝 The Torah gives us an amazing tool: If you see someone doing something wrong, don't just stay quiet or gossip about it - help them grow! Here's the key: Speak privately, gently, and make it clear you're coming from a place of love. Did you know? The word for rebuke (תוכחה) is related to the word for proof (הוכחה), teaching us to help others see proof of a better way! Today's challenge: If you need to give feedback, do it with kindness and wisdom.": "Овладейте искусством любящего упрека! 💝 Тора: «Укори ближнего» (Ваикра 19:17). Говорите наедине, мягко, из любви. Тохаха связана с «доказательством» лучшего пути. Сегодня: дайте обратную связь с добротой.",
    "Minhag": "минhаг",
    "Ne'ilah": "неила",
    "Neshama is the soul — the divine breath that makes you alive. Modeh Ani thanks G-d for returning it after sleep. Yizkor and Kaddish relate to the soul's journey after death. Jewish thought distinguishes levels of soul (nefesh, ruach, neshama) in mysticism; practically, nurturing the soul means Torah, mitzvot, and character.": "нешама — душа, божественное дыхание, дарующее жизнь. Моде ани благодарит В-га за возвращение её после сна. Йизкор и Кадиш связаны с путём души. На практике — Тора, мицвот и характер.",
    "Niddah is the state of ritual separation during and after menstruation until mikveh immersion. Husband and wife avoid physical intimacy and certain affectionate contact. Laws of stains and cycles are complex — a kallah teacher or rav supports real-life questions. Niddah is not a punishment; it is rhythm and holiness in marriage.": "нида — ритуальное разделение во время и после менструации до погружения в микве. Законы пятен сложны — учительница каллы или рав помогает. Это ритм и святость брака, не наказание.",
    "Nusach Ari is the prayer rite associated with Rabbi Isaac Luria (the Ari) and used by Chabad and some other communities. It blends Ashkenazi and Sephardi elements. Chabad siddurim such as Tehillat Hashem print this nusach. If you daven Nusach Ari, use that siddur consistently for festival inserts.": "нусах Ари — молитвенный обряд раввина Ицхака Лурии; используют Хабад и другие общины. Сочетает ашкеназские и сефардские элементы. Для праздничных вставок — сидур Техилат Хашем.",
    "Plag HaMincha": "плаг hа-минха",
    "Practice Emunah (faith)! Take a deep breath and remember that everything in your life is orchestrated by G-d with perfect precision 🎯. Each challenge is custom-designed to help you grow, and every joy is a personal gift from Above. When we strengthen our trust in G-d's plan, we find inner peace and purpose.": "Практикуйте эмуну! 🎯 Всё устроено В-гом. Каждое испытание — для роста, каждая радость — дар свыше. Доверие к плану В-га даёт покой и смысл.",
    "Purim joy includes everyone! 🎭💝 Learn about matanot la'evyonim (gifts to the poor): halacha teaches that Purim simcha is incomplete if people in need are left out. It's a requirement of the day to give at least a small sum (preferably enough to buy a meal) to 2 different poor people on Purim. You can also give the money to someone else to distribute it for you, but they need to distribute it on the same day that you celebrate Purim (the 14th or 15th of Adar). Learn one law about this beautiful mitzvah!": "Радость Пурима — для всех! 🎭💝 Матанот ла-эвьоним — подарки бедным (Мегилла 7а). Дайте хотя бы двум нуждающим в день Пурима. Можно поручить распределение — в тот же день. Узнайте больше!",
    "Shamor": "шамор",
    "Share in another parent's hopes! Think of someone who needs nachat (joy and pride from their children) and say a heartfelt prayer for them 👨‍👩‍👧‍👦. Whether it's for health, success, or happiness - your caring thoughts can make a real difference for both the parents and their children! ❤️": "Поделитесь надеждами другого родителя! 👨‍👩‍👧‍👦 Помолитесь за того, кому нужен нахат — радость от детей. ❤️",
    "Shomer Daltot Yisrael": "Шомер далтот Исраэль",
    "Ta'anit": "таанит",
    "Ta'anit — a public or personal fast day": "таанит — публичный или личный пост",
    "Taanit Esther": "таанит Эстер",
    "Taanit Esther — fast day before Purim": "таанит Эстер — пост перед Пуримом",
    "The Days of Awe (Aseret Yemei Teshuvah) span Rosh Hashana through Yom Kippur — a time of judgment, prayer, and teshuvah. Customs intensify: Selichot, charity, and asking forgiveness. Even Jews who are less observant year-round often attend services. The tone is solemn but hopeful — repentance can change a harsh decree.": "Дни Страха (Асерет йемей тшува) — от Рош а-Шана до Йом Кипура: суд, молитва, тешува. Селихот, тредака, прощение. Тон торжественный, но с надеждой — покаяние может изменить указ.",
    "Tochen": "тохен",
    "Tochen — grinding melacha": "тохен — мелаха помола",
    "Tzniut is one of the defining values of Jewish life — it governs how we dress and how we carry ourselves in the world.\n\nWhat tzniut is:\nTzniut (צְנִיעוּת — modesty) comes from the verse \"Walk humbly (hatznea lechet) with your G-d\" (Micah 6:8). It is not just a dress code — it is a philosophy of life. Tzniut means reserving what is most precious and intimate for those who truly know you, rather than displaying it to the world.\n\nIn dress (for women):\n• Skirts or dresses that cover the knees\n• Tops that cover the elbows and collarbone\n• Avoid tight-fitting or sheer clothing\n• Stockings / tights as required by community custom\n\nIn conduct (for everyone):\n• Speak with dignity and thoughtfulness\n• Do not seek unnecessary attention\n• Act in a way that reflects inner character over outer appearance\n• Lower the eyes when appropriate\n\nFor men:\nTzniut applies to men too — in dress, speech, and conduct. Men should not wear revealing clothing and should conduct themselves with dignity.\n\nStandards vary by community. The key is sincere progress and consistency, guided by your local rabbi and rebbetzin.": "Цниют — одна из главных ценностей еврейской жизни: одежда и поведение.\n\nЦниют (צְנִיעוּת) — «иди смиренно с Б-гом твоим» (Миха 6:8). Не только дресс-код, а философия: сохранять ценное для близких, а не выставлять напоказ.\n\nОдежда (женщины): юбки/платья ниже колен, рукава до локтей, закрытая ключица, без облегающего.\n\nПоведение (все): достоинство в речи, без лишнего внимания, внутренний характер важнее внешности.\n\nМужчинам тоже. Стандарты различаются — спросите рава и ребецин.",
    "When you acquire new metal or glass dishes, pots, or utensils that were manufactured by a non-Jew, they require ritual immersion (Tevilat Keilim) before they can touch food. Glazed ceramic (such as china or porcelain with a glaze) and similar materials often require immersion as well — usually without a bracha.\n\nWho triggers the obligation: the manufacturer who made the item — not the store that sold it. A pot made by a non-Jewish company still requires tevilah even if you bought it from a Jewish-owned shop; a pot made by a Jew does not require tevilah even if you bought it from a non-Jewish retailer. Ask your rav about borderline cases.\n\nWhat this is:\nTevilat keilim (טְבִילַת כֵּלִים — \"immersion of vessels\") is a mitzvah derived from Numbers 31:23. Most poskim treat it as rabbinic today; some view it as Torah-level — ask your rav. Just as the human body requires immersion for certain transitions, so too do our vessels when entering the Jewish home.\n\nWhich vessels need immersion:\n• With a blessing: metal and glass vessels used for food\n• Without a blessing (rabbinic requirement): glazed ceramic and some other materials — ask your rabbi for unusual items\n• No immersion needed: plastic, wooden items, disposables, and items manufactured by a Jew\n\nHow to do it:\nRecite the blessing, then fully submerge the vessel. Let go for a moment so the water surrounds the entire item — a brief release ensures nothing is still touching your hand above the waterline. Use a kosher mikveh; if there is no mikveh nearby, you may immerse in the ocean, a lake, or a river — whether a particular body of water qualifies depends on several factors, so ask your rabbi. Your local mikveh or rabbi can advise on times and setup.\n\nOvens and appliances:\nFor ovens and similar items, usually only the removable racks (or parts that directly touch food) are immersed — not the entire appliance. Some items do require immersing the whole unit; halacha depends on the type. If you are worried about damage — digital displays, electronics, or fragile equipment — ask your rabbi; sometimes one may be lenient and not immerse.\n\nThis is a situational mitzvah — check it off when you have completed immersing the required vessels.": "Новая металлическая или стеклянная посуда от нееврея требует тевилат кеилим перед контактом с едой. Глазурованная керамика часто тоже — обычно без брахи.\n\nОбязанность от производителя, не от магазина. Пластик и дерево — без тевилы.\n\nПолное погружение в микве; отпустите предмет на мгновение. Для печей — обычно только решётки. Спросите рава.",
    "Why Shnayim Mikra is worth the effort — teachings of our rabbis:\n\nThe weekly Torah portion is not only a calendar item. It is your personal share in the Torah that sustains the Jewish people. The sages tie public Torah reading to the survival of the world itself (Shabbat 119b). When you learn the same parsha the community will hear on Shabbat, you join a chain stretching back to Sinai — and the Shechinah dwells wherever words of Torah are spoken (Avot 3:2).\n\nTorah study protects the learner; it is among the three guardians of life in the Talmud (Sotah 21a). Tradition describes words of Torah ascending and bringing merit. Shnayim Mikra is a manageable weekly rhythm: a little each day builds a bond with Hashem that no podcast can replace.\n\nEach week, the Jewish community reads a designated section of the Torah in synagogue on Shabbat morning. Every individual is personally required to study that same section during the week.\n\nWhat this is:\nShnayim Mikra v'Echad Targum (שְׁנַיִם מִקְרָא וְאֶחָד תַּרְגּוּם — \"twice the text and once the translation\") is the requirement to read each verse of the weekly Torah portion:\n• Twice in the original Hebrew\n• Once in Aramaic translation (Targum Onkelos) or Rashi's commentary, which many use as a substitute for the translation to better understand the plain meaning (Shulchan Arukh and Mishnah Berurah O.C. 285:2)\n\nFor those learning Hebrew:\nIf you cannot yet read the Hebrew and Aramaic fluently, you can read from a transliterated Chumash, and many authorities allow an accurate English translation in place of Targum Onkelos. However, learning to read the Hebrew text is one of the most rewarding investments a Jew can make.\n\nWhen to do it (Shulchan Arukh O.C. 285:4):\n• L'chatchila (ideal): finish before you eat on Shabbat — before the Shabbat meal and ideally before the public Torah reading.\n• If not finished before the meal: complete it after the meal, before Mincha on Shabbat.\n• If you still fell behind: some poskim allow until Wednesday of the following week; others until Simchat Torah, when the congregation completes the annual cycle (see commentaries on O.C. 285:4).\n\nMost people spread the parsha across the week — a few verses or an aliyah each day. Missing the ideal pre-Shabbat morning window does not mean the mitzvah is lost; these fallback times remain valid until they pass.\n\nHow this checklist tracks it: the item stays available through Shabbat (not marked failed at Friday night). A new parsha appears when the calendar week turns; if you fell behind on the prior portion, you may still make it up per O.C. 285:4 even after the new parsha shows here.": "Почему Шнайим Микра стоит усилий:\n\nЕженедельная параша — ваша доля в Торе. Читайте каждый стих дважды на иврите и один раз в Таргум Онкелос или Раши (О.Х. 285).\nИдеал — до трапезы в Шаббат; иначе — до Минхи или до среды следующей недели по посеким.",
    "Yizkor": "йизкор",
    "Yizkor is the memorial prayer on Yom Tov (and Yom Kippur) for parents and sometimes other relatives. Many light a yahrzeit candle before the day. Pledging charity in their memory is a beautiful custom. Those with both parents living often leave the shul briefly per minhag. The prayer affirms that merit and memory continue beyond death.": "Йизкор — мемориальная молитва в Йом Тов и Йом Кипур за ушедших. Зажигают свечу, дают тредаку. У кого оба родителя живы — часто выходят из синагоги по минhагу.",
    "Yizkor — Yizkor is the memorial prayer on Yom Tov (and Yom Kippur) for parents and sometimes other relatives. Many light a yahrzeit candle before the day. Pledging charity in their memory is a beautiful custom. Those with both parents living often leave the shul briefly per minhag. The prayer affirms that merit and memory continue beyond death.": "йизкор — мемориальная молитва в праздники и Йом Кипур за ушедших",
    "aliyah": "алия",
    "biur chametz": "биур хамец",
    "candles, often referring especially to Shabbat and Yom Tov lights": "свечи, часто шабатные и праздничные",
    "challah — Challah is the bread often prepared for Shabbat and festival meals — often braided and covered until Kiddush. Two loaves (lechem mishneh) recall the double portion in the desert. On Friday night, if wine or grape juice is completely unavailable, Kiddush can be recited over the challah loaves, provided one washes hands for bread immediately before reciting Kiddush and replaces the wine blessing with Hamotzi. Bread can never substitute for daytime Shabbat Kiddush on Saturday morning.": "хала — хлеб для Шабата и праздников; две буханки (лехем мишне). В пятницу вечером без вина — киддуш над халой с ха-моци; утром в Шаббат хлеб не заменяет киддуш.",
    "charoset — Charoset is the sweet paste (apples, wine, nuts, etc.) recalling mortar between bricks. It is dipped with maror for Korech. Recipes vary by family — Ashkenazi, Sephardi, and Persian charoset all fulfill the mitzvah when made with intent. It is one of the Seder plate's sensory contrasts: bitter and sweet together.": "харосет — сладкая паста на Седере (яблоки, вино, орехи), напоминающая раствор; с марором в корехе.",
    "halachic hour — A halachic hour (sha'ah zmanit) is one twelfth of the daylight period from dawn to dusk — so it is longer in summer and shorter in winter, unlike a 60-minute clock hour. Deadlines such as latest morning Shema, chametz sale times, and plag hamincha use these hours. Apps and Jewish calendars convert them for your location.": "ша'а зманит — галахический час: 1/12 светового дня; длиннее летом, короче зимой. Используется для крайнего срока Шмы, продажи хамеца, плаг hа-минхи.",
    "kallah": "калла",
    "kippah": "кипа",
    "kippah — skullcap worn as a sign of G-d's presence above": "кипа — знак присутствия В-га над нами",
    "lechem mishneh": "лехем мишне",
    "maaser kesafim — Maaser kesafim is setting aside about ten percent of net income for tzedakah after expenses. It trains that income is entrusted, not owned absolutely. Priorities: local poor, Torah learning, Israel. If you cannot give ten percent without hardship, give what you can and ask your rav.": "маасер кесафим — ~10% дохода на тредаку; приоритеты: бедные, Тора, Израиль.",
}

